When diving into JavaScript, you'll quickly come across different tools that help make your code more efficient and readable. In this post, we‚Äôll explore three essential concepts:
while loop
map() function
arrow functions (=>)
Let‚Äôs break them down with simple examples.
while Loop


A while loop runs as long as a certain condition is true. It‚Äôs useful when you don‚Äôt know exactly how many times the loop should run.
while (condition) {
  // code to run
}

let i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
  console.log("Number:", i);
  i++;
}

The loop checks if i < 5

If true, it runs the code inside
i++ increases i by 1 each time
When i hits 5, the loop stops
map() Function


The map() function is used to transform each item in an array and return a new array with the results.
let newArray = oldArray.map(callbackFunction);

let numbers = [1, 2, 3];
let doubled = numbers.map(function(num) {
  return num * 2;
});

console.log(doubled); // [2, 4, 6]

Arrow functions are a shorter way to write functions. They‚Äôre especially useful with methods like map().
const functionName = (parameters) => {
  // function body
};

Here‚Äôs the same map() example with an arrow function:
let numbers = [1, 2, 3];
let doubled = numbers.map(num => num * 2);

console.log(doubled); // [2, 4, 6]

üìù If there‚Äôs only one parameter and one expression, you can skip the parentheses and curly braces.
Let‚Äôs say you want to double the numbers in an array using a while loop and arrow functions.
let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];
let doubled = [];

let i = 0;
while (i < numbers.length) {
  doubled.push((num => num * 2)(numbers[i]));
  i++;
}

console.log(doubled); // [2, 4, 6, 8]

